{"type":"message-part","messageId":"5cc98973-0f7a-41a9-809a-340db1dc9b63","role":"user","index":0,"part":{"type":"text","text":"# Jujutsu Alias Configuration\n\n## Background\nJujutsu (`jj`) allows you to define command aliases to simplify your workflow. You can configure these globally for your user.\n\n## Requirements\n1. Initialize a new `jj` repository collocated with git in `/home/user/myproject`.\n2. Configure the `jj` user name as \"Test User\" and email as \"test@example.com\".\n3. Configure a user-level `jj` alias named `mylog` that translates to `log -r @-`.\n4. Create a file `hello.txt` with the content `Hello jj` in the project.\n5. Record the change by creating a new commit with the message `Add hello.txt` (e.g., using `jj new -m \"Add hello.txt\"` or `jj commit -m \"Add hello.txt\"`).\n\n## Constraints\n- Project path: `/home/user/myproject`\n- The alias must be a user-level configuration (using `jj config set --user`).\n- The alias `mylog` should execute `log` with the arguments `-r` and `@-`."}}
{"type":"message-part","messageId":"5cc98973-0f7a-41a9-809a-340db1dc9b63","role":"user","index":0,"part":{"type":"text","text":"<system-reminder># System Information\n\nOperating System: linux\nDefault Shell: \nHome Directory: /root\nCurrent Working Directory: /\nCurrent Time: Wed Apr 15 2026 02:27:58 GMT+0000 (Coordinated Universal Time)\n\n# GIT STATUS\nCurrent branch: \nMain branch (you will usually use this for PRs): \n\nRecent commits:\n\n\n# TODOs\nNo TODOs yet, if you are working on tasks that would benefit from a todo list please use the todoWrite tool to create one.</system-reminder>"}}
{"type":"message-part","messageId":"5cc98973-0f7a-41a9-809a-340db1dc9b63","role":"user","index":1,"part":{"type":"text","text":"# Jujutsu Alias Configuration\n\n## Background\nJujutsu (`jj`) allows you to define command aliases to simplify your workflow. You can configure these globally for your user.\n\n## Requirements\n1. Initialize a new `jj` repository collocated with git in `/home/user/myproject`.\n2. Configure the `jj` user name as \"Test User\" and email as \"test@example.com\".\n3. Configure a user-level `jj` alias named `mylog` that translates to `log -r @-`.\n4. Create a file `hello.txt` with the content `Hello jj` in the project.\n5. Record the change by creating a new commit with the message `Add hello.txt` (e.g., using `jj new -m \"Add hello.txt\"` or `jj commit -m \"Add hello.txt\"`).\n\n## Constraints\n- Project path: `/home/user/myproject`\n- The alias must be a user-level configuration (using `jj config set --user`).\n- The alias `mylog` should execute `log` with the arguments `-r` and `@-`."}}
